\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 against telephone use while evaluating carefully other technological options. Research on users\'92 practices has advanced significantly in studies about Western Europe and the United States, thanks to Science and Technology Studies especially, revealing that users shaped new technologies according to their needs through networking, tinkering, and tweaking.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 6 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Additionally, researchers have shown that analyzing non-users is relevant for assessing the reception of a technology in everyday life. Resistance, avoidance or lack of access to technological items can also develop a transformative power.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 7 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Finally, the concept of imagined use permits scholars to understand the discourses and mentalities shaping engagement with technologies, especially in regions where large sectors of the population lacked access to certain technologies.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 8 
\fs24 \cf2 \up0 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 Overall, the history of the telephone has oscillated between three analytic approaches. The history of technology has mainly considered the technical dimensions of telephone networks, apparatus, and switchboards and, more recently, the way users have shaped or reshaped telephone technologies.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 9 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Scholarship on the political economy of communication has mainly studied economic aspects of the medium, such as the history of telephone enterprises, network expansion, legal environments, and relations of power made manifest over telephone lines.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 10 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Lastly, beginning in the 1980s, mainly with a cultural studies perspective, researchers have explored social and cultural change brought about by the telephone, considering debates about privacy, gender relations, time management, and the development of a telephone etiquette.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 11 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 These studies recognized telephone users as important historical actors and homes as the key places where the telephone finds its ecology.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 12 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 By inserting itself into private lives, homes and business offices, the medium has become an important one for daily communication, either in its landline or in its wireless manifestations, and ultimately a motor for changing global communication habits. Each of these approaches has illuminated some aspects of the medium, but it is time to transcend national boundaries, overcome mono-medial and mono-usage perspectives and bring different research traditions into a new dialogue. 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf3 Towards a new history of the telephone: ideas from this special issue 
\fs24 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 The contributions in this special issue consider the history of the telephone from several perspectives. Indeed, as mentioned, new histories of the telephone are needed in different geographic spaces and different historical times. In terms of periodization, this special issue covers nearly the entire twentieth century, from the First World War to the 1990s, when the World Wide Web was about to rise. Until now, the majority of research has concentrated on the early years of landline networks and then the expan- sion of the mobile phone from the 1990s onward. As the articles in this special issue show, the period from the 1920s to the 1980s is very fruitful for explaining changes in communication (and telephone) culture, and the rise of transnational expert networks, as well as questioning the analog-digital divide in media historiography. This does not mean that early and later stages of the telephone history are studied sufficiently, and we hope this special issue may inspire studying these eras differently and even stretching temporalities of the telephone history before the technology\'92s \'91official\'92 invention in the 1870s. 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 {{\NeXTGraphic page3image11375904.png \width220 \height220 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 In terms of geographic spaces, the contributions include a transnational dimension and/or situate case studies in a comparative framework. Richard John and L\'e9onard Laborie
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 13 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 focus on transnational telephone communications during the First World War. Wars are generally considered moments when national interests prevail over transnational collaboration, but this paper shows how the \'91practicality of transnational telephony\'92 (as Theodor Vail formulated it) prevailed over wartime urgencies \'96 and satisfied the desire of the American Telephone and Telegraph Company to expand in the European market. Similarly, Patryk Wasiak characterizes the software piracy scene as the first transnational network to accomplish a nearly instantaneous exchange of media objects. At first, this exchange was limited to the United States and Western Europe, with a strategic advantage for US users, as these could use telephone networks within their flat rate tariffs. New transnational contacts provided prestige to scene members who expanded their networks to other continents in the 1990s. However, not all communication networks allowed for transnational exchanges. Coreen Anne McGuire, in her paper on the categorization of hearing loss through deployments of the telephone, shows for example that public institutions like the British Post Office and private ones, like the American AT&T, did not share the same \'91telephone cultures\'92 and so they brought different forms of attention to users with hearing limitations. Also in the case of CB radio described here by Heike Weber, users were unable to cross national borders due to limited outreach and legal regulation. Consequently, regional clubs remained the most popular form for social organizing. Weber also shows that there was a rich variety of CB radio cultures around the globe, which research has not previously explored. In sum, these papers move beyond the nation-state as the principal framework for telephone history by either including a comparative perspective or focusing on transnational exchanges. This is a starting point for discussing problems and opportunities of an international circulation of \'91telephone cultures\'92. 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 A second new direction taken by this special issue is what we call an intermedia or inter-technological perspective. Media scholars agree on the fact that different media are all interrelated and they have coined the terms intermedia or media system logic to describe these circumstances.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 14 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Thus, communication technologies cannot be studied in isolation and their political, economic, technical, socio-cultural and even anthropological dimensions can only emerge in the context of the media ecologies of which they are an integral part. Hence, this issue explores telephone history through its interaction with other media and other technologies in order both to expand the concept of a one-to-one medium and to reconsider the role, impact or interaction that the telephone had on or with other media and technol- ogies. The ecologies in which the telephone acted and acts are broad. In a professional environment, the telephone was situated in a setting of diverse office technologies such as typewriters, telefax, pagers, and computers.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 15 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Moving beyond the office, it also heavily influenced transport logistics, surveillance systems, and public transport. In private homes, the telephone interacted with household appli- ances and other media, for instance, radio or television.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 16 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 With telephony becoming increasingly mobile, the possibility of intermedia interactions increased. Smartphones, for example, allowed for reassembling different media into the mobile phone, which marks the last stage of intermedia change in telephone history thus far.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 17 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 The very notion of intermedia and inter-technological developments suggests 
