\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 that our previous demarcation of individual technologies (like the telephone) may have been limiting our explanatory historical possibilities and it allows for defining a new role and relevance of the telephone among other technologies (not only of communication), as well as in everyday lives and social practices. 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 John and Laborie place the telephone in a particular ecology where telegraphy, photography, direction finding, wireless telegraphy and several other technologies of communication were experimented with and used at the same time. In this situation, the telephone and the telegraph sometimes complemented each other but also com- peted. Similarly, Wasiak applies an intermedia approach in his paper, considering the telephone in combination with computers and early forms of digital distribution of information. The telephone, in other words, is part of the history of the internet and, conversely, the history of the internet should be narrated more and more in \'91telephonic\'92 terms. 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 But this special issue shows how the telephone has interacted with, shaped, and changed not only technologies of communication (and so it has had not only an intermedia effect), but has also impacted technologies that are not intended for com- municating. This is what we call the inter-technological perspective. Coreen Anne McGuire embraces this perspective, giving the telephone a key role in the history of medicine and, especially, the history of technologies of disability. In the 1920s and 1930s, the British Post Office marketed a \'91Telephone for deaf subscribers\'92 with special technologies of amplification for those users. We engage here with the history of the telephone and history of microphones, the history of medicine, the history of technol- ogies of hearing, and of hearing per se. This paper shows how all these dimensions must be combined if one wants to understand the multiple roles the telephone has had in contemporary societies, besides being a device for one-to-one communication (several papers refer to STS literature describing the telephone as having a high \'91interpretative flexibility\'92).
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 18 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 Another example of this kind is Weber\'92s paper on the relation between CB technologies and trucks and cars, namely the relation between communication and transportation. Considering transportation and communication as a single entity, under the umbrella-concept of mobility, is a needed move for contemporary research in media and transportation studies
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 19 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 and the telephone is one the most symbolic trait d\'92union between the two fields: wireless telephony in the early twentieth century as well as smartphones today have been experimented with and used especially in connection with transportation technologies such as trains, ships, planes, cars, shuttles, and prob- ably virtually all other forms of transportation. 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 This special issue can also contribute to the literature of technological standards. Wars have challenged transnational communication but also favored technological integration. John and Laborie show in their contribution how the First World War facilitated the breakthrough of US. technological standards in Europe. The US Signal Corps, responsible for military communication, expanded telephone networks in France significantly based on US technological protocols. This happened in a period when multinational companies fiercely competed on global telephone markets. John and Laborie also demonstrate that the close personal links between French and US engineers ensured the application of US standards during the inter-war period. French engineers significantly influenced the committees responsible for standard- setting in long-distance telephony (CCIF). The telephone also contributed to 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 {{\NeXTGraphic page3image11375904.png \width220 \height220 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 standard-setting in other areas, such as medicine/audiometry and disability. As McGuire argues, by defining certain audibility levels as normal, the British tele- phone company categorized all people that did not meet these levels as \'91deaf subscribers\'92, which recirculated a social stigma. This had also medical implications because the telephone service for deaf people \'91became the arbiter of a medical condition\'92; in other words, the telephone impacted directly the production and use of medical standards \'96 a historical relation that we are not used to considering. 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 The contributions in this issue also confirm the active role that users played in adapting telephones or the networks\'92 infrastructure to their needs. They show how people in different contexts struggled with state monopolies and private companies over unexpected use practices and technical adaptations. For example, people with hearing limitations created new devices to gain access to telephone communication. West Germans widely used unauthorized CB radio equipment as an alternative to landline telephones, while a software pirate scene appropriated the network\'92s infrastructure for exchanging data packages. In creating niche rooms for instantaneous exchange, these subcultures designed new spaces for informal chats and software exchange. This was in line with new participative media formats developing in the 1970s and 1980s, as Weber shows in her article. For their communication, subcultures designed a special etiquette, relying on unconventional nicknames or cover names as well as acronyms. While the software pirates perceived technical obstacles and restrictions as a technological chal- lenge, CB radio users also mobilized politically against the restrictions established by state monopolies. Interestingly, both subcultures were dominated by male users who, in the case of CB radio, regularly shared sexist content in specialized journals. By contrast, the majority of existing research has exclusively focused on female telephone commu- nication as well as the role of female operators.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 20 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 More generally, users often try to go beyond the \'91script\'92 created by telephone companies, governments, and technical stan- dardization. This engages a popular concept in Actor-Network Theory: according to Bruno Latour and Madeleine Akrich, for example, technical objects contain specific \'91programs\'92 on how to use them, but these programs are often modified by users, who re-write and re-use instruments with different purposes and goals than those expected by their instigators.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 21 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 So the telephone has often changed its apparently given \'91nature\'92 and was historically used for alternative scopes other than one-to-one communication among people: \'91measuring\'92 hearing limitations, political engagement, or exchanging data are just some examples. 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf3 Why is this special issue interesting for media historians and historians of technology? 
\fs24 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 This special issue is special for historians of the telephone, but our hope is that it can be special for media historians and historians of technology as well. Media historians, for example, may reconsider the role of the telephone and so rethink \'91classic\'92 media history in new and radical terms. To us, this special issue represents just one of the first steps towards a telephonic history of the media or, put differently, an invitation to place the telephone (in cultural, technical, and political terms) at the center of several media histories. Journalists used the telephone from its inception to transmit their pieces to newsrooms and, similarly, telephone companies provided special services to the press 
