\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 such as the transmission of pictures or printing of newspapers at home, with tools that can be seen as ancestors of fax or contemporary digital distribution of the press. Forms of radio and TV broadcasting over telephone lines were usual in several countries and can be considered a form of media convergence underway well before digitization. Computer networks, later known as the Internet, used telephone networks to transfer data from one user to another. The last case, for example, invites us on the one hand to rethink the history of computers and the Internet telephonically and, on the other, to fight against a clear division between analog and digital forms of communication, since telephone networks carrying digital data were in fact analog for long time. The distinction between analog and digital media is a recurring mistake and topos of contemporary digital media scholarship. Digital media are seen as disruptive, revolu- tionary, and more in general different from analog ones. But if we look carefully at their development (or, in other words, if we study their histories), we notice several con- tinuities and degrees of persistence of analog media in the digital world, we realize how digital media have sometimes reinforced analog ones, and how the same meanings of analog and digital are much more blurred than what we think.
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 22 
\fs24 \cf2 \up0 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 As we said, the history and impact of the telephone goes also beyond media studies and we hope historians of technology will consider it more often. In this special issue, historians of medicine, and specifically of disability, can find interesting insights on the social construction of deafness during the twentieth-century in Britain and how the telephone set standards and was used to create new aural experiences. Historians of transportation can rethink people\'92s flows and movements in the 1970s and 1980s in West Germany, how these new forms of mobility were allowed and shaped by CBs and, more generally, how the telephone contributed to changing and to shaping the experience of travelling. Historians of technical stan- dards, as well, can find interesting case studies where the telephone helped to set or to challenge standards. But thinking more broadly, the telephone has a key space in several histories of technologies. For example, historians of networks and infrastruc- tures (such as road, electric, gas, water and other systems) can think about the similarities with telephone networks and how the telephone often constituted an info-structure to maintain and distribute information over these networks. Historians of house technologies, such as systems and materials of housekeeping, could think about the domestic status of the telephone and its role in giving orders, relief to work, and bringing public space into private ones. We could also rethink the history of technological accidents, considering how the telephone was seen as an emergency tool to sound alarms or even to avoid accidents (probably the most symbolic and over-estimated was the red phone between Washington and Moscow
\fs18\fsmilli9333 \cf4 \up13 23
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 \up0 ). Within the history of sexual and erotic technologies, the telephone is not often considered, but it can be placed at the same level as vibrators and bullwhips as a means to turn on (another media/telephonic metaphor) sexual part- ners. ... And many other examples can be added. 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 In conclusion, the goal of this special issue is not only to extend knowledge of the history of the telephone with new case studies and unconventional approaches, but also to start a discussion and to inspire further research towards a telephonic history of communication and non-communication technologies. Indeed, instead of being trea- ted as peripheral or ancillary to various histories of technologies, the telephone has to 
